// about screen About the App Need help determining whether your food is the right choice for YOU? With Nutrition Checker, you can find out how healthy the food that you want to eat is by simply taking a photo of its nutrition label. Once you provide info such as your age, sex, height, and weight, this app can help determine how nutritious the food is specifically for you. 

Physical fitness has been neglected by many people as the coronavirus has pervaded the world. Most individuals aren’t staying as active while also eating unhealthy or “junk” foods, which is detrimental to their physical fitness. What we’ve done is create a simple remedy to the problem by providing a tool that informs users what foods are healthy and should be eaten and what foods are unhealthy to help people make better choices while buying and eating food. By informing individuals about the unhealthy ingredients in food items, users can maintain their physical fitness levels while staying at home during this global pandemic. 

We use OCR or optical character recognition to convert the text from the label to a string. From there, we parse the total amounts of various components per serving and compare these values to the recommended amounts as prescribed by leading health organizations such as WHO, FDA, and the American Heart Association. Getting Started If you need some additional help getting started with Nutrition Checker, please go through the following instructions:

1. On the home screen, you will find your past food items that you have scanned labels for in your cart. If you have not scanned anything, no items will show up.

2.Before, you click the "Scan Label" button to take a photo of the nutrition label of your food or drink, make sure that your personal info is correct. Check your profile which contains your personal info that you entered when you first opened up the app. If you need to make any changes, then go ahead and edit your profile.

3. After your info is correct, go back to the Home screen and press the button to scan your label. Take a picture of the nutrition label and retake the photo if it is messy.

4. Check to see if the photo that appears on the screen when your return from your camera has good resolution and is right-side up. If it is not, click the button to take a photo again until you believe you have a good photo because the text will not be read properly with a blurry photo that is not oriented correctly.

5. Once you confirm your photo, you will see the nutrition info and be able to add the item to your cart.

6.If you want to scan another item, take another photo and then add it to the cart. If your results are good, keep it up! Otherwise, make better choices. Credits Sooraj V. Chetput
